ly handles what git actually returns. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: The behavior's failure mode is a real subprocess exit code and stderr message from git on an edge-case repo state; no in-process fake can reproduce that without assuming what we are supposed to be verifying.","test_description":"In a temp directory, run 'git init' but make no commits; invoke the CLI tool pointing at that directory; assert the process exits with code 0 and that the structured output contains zero entries in every category (added, deleted, renamed, modified) rather than a stack trace or non-zero exit.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The counts in the report match the actual change history of the repository being analyzed.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Count accuracy must be verified against ground truth that comes from real git history, not a fixture we define ourselves. If we mock git output, the test only proves our mock matches our expectation — not that the tool correctly processes real git output for arbitrary histories. REAL-INFRA: The tool reads real git history via subprocess; the test must set up real commits with known operations (add 3 files, delete 1, rename 1, modify 2) and then run the tool against that real repo. MOCK-HIDE: A mocked subprocess would always pass trivially — the assertion would be validating our own fixture, not the tool's accuracy. REJECTION-GATE: 'Actual change history' is explicit in the behavior text — the word 'actual' disqualifies any fixture-based approach and mandates real git state.","test_description":"Create a real temp git repo via subprocess; make a scripted sequence of commits that adds 3 files, modifies 2, renames 1, and deletes 1; run the CLI tool; assert the output report shows exactly those counts per category.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The output is identical whether the changes being analyzed are staged or unstaged.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is that the tool produces different results depending on whether it queries the git index ('git diff --cached') vs the working tree ('git diff'), meaning the two code paths diverge. REAL-INFRA: Git staging is an OS-level filesystem/index operation; 'git add' updates the index on disk and the resulting difference between staged and unstaged state is a real subprocess/OS behavior that cannot be faithfully reproduced by an in-process fake. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking both subprocess calls would force them to return identical output trivially — the test would always pass regardless of whether the tool actually uses different git flags for staged vs unstaged. REJECTION-GATE: The behavior's failure mode (divergent output between staged and unstaged) only appears when both real git index state and real git working-tree state are populated and the tool runs real queries against both; no in-process stub can expose that divergence.","test_description":"Create a real temp git repo with an initial commit; make a set of file changes and 'git add' them (staged); run the tool in staged mode; then make the same changes from a fresh checkout but do NOT stage them (unstaged); run the tool in unstaged mode; assert the two output reports are byte-for-byte identical.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.81,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12833,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":12833},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"no